 as a second language. The particular concern for the language is the spread to younger generations, while there are immersion programs for young Navajo: there are only 30%25 of L1 speakers among Navajo first-graders in 1998 which is a steep decline from the 90%25 of L1 speakers in 1968. This is mostly due to a shift towards speaking English primarily as the Navajo language falls to the wayside and is saved for mostly official purposes and for celebration of heritage amongst this younger generation. %0a%3c %0a%3c This hasn't gone without notice from the tribe though, as the tribal government as well as outside institutions take active measures to help preserve the language and revitalize it through, as mentioned before, immersion programs as well as offering language courses in many large universities. %0a%3c %0a%3c sources:%0a%3c http://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/6085%0a%3c https://www.ethnologue.com/language/nav%0a%3c https://www.hcn.org/issues/47.4/most-native-tongues-of-the-west-are-all-but-lost%0a%3c https://www.researchgate.net/publication/241045409_Dine_Bizaad_Navajo_Language_at_a_Crossroads_Extinction_or_Renewal%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
